The Abuja Memorandum of Understanding on Port State Control is set to host 21 Directors General of maritime administrations across West and Central Africa in Nigeria from May 9-11, 2022 for a training programme Captain Sunday Umoren , Secretary General of Abuja MoU, has confirmed. He disclosed that the event which is being sponsored by the International Maritime Organisation (IMO) ,has also received endorsement of the Federal Ministry of Transportation (FMoT) Umoren added that the training event is part of Abuja MoU drive to keep Chief Executives of maritime administrations abreast with the required knowledge for port state control and achieve operational harmony in line with global best practices. According to the Secretary General, the training will achieve many goals including discouragement of substandard ships from the shores of West and Central Africa Captain Umoren stated further that the Port State control training for DGs will serve as refresher and sharpen their knowledge of inspection of foreign ships visiting the ports of member countries. The training, according to him, will harp on the need to enforce high compliance level of the ships with relevant international conventions and codes governing maritime safety, marine pollution and the living and working conditions of seafarers on board ships.